      <div xml:id="NA355-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu tōḻi arukaṭuttatu. 2. tōḻi talaimakaḷatu (G1+2: talaimakaḷ taṉatu) āṟṟāmai kaṇṭu varaivu kaṭāyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante came near [the matter]. 2. It is also how the confidante asked for marriage when seeing HER unability to bear it.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA355">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            putalva ṉīṉṟa pūṅkaṇ maṭantai</l>
<l>            mulaivā yuṟukkuṅ kaipōṟ kāntaṭ</l>
<l>            kulaivāy tōyuṅ koḻumaṭal vāḻai</l>
<l>            yammaṭaṟ paṭṭa varuvit tīnīr</l>
<l>            cemmuka manti yāru nāṭa</l>
<l>            muntai yiruntu naṭṭōr koṭuppi</l>
<l>            ṉañcu muṇpar naṉinā karika</l>
<l>            rañci lōtiyeṉ ṟōḻi tōṭṭuyi</l>
<l>            ṉeñci ṉiṉpuṟā yāyiṉu matunī</l>
<l>            yeṉka ṇōṭi yaḷimati</l>
<l>            niṉka ṇallatu piṟitiyātu milaḷē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            O man from a land, where the red-faced female monkey becomes full</l>
<l rend="indent">            of the sweet water from the waterfall that came from the pretty leaves</l>
<l rend="indent2">            of the plantain with rich fronds that touch the clustered [flower-]mouths</l>
<l rend="indent3">            of the Malabar lily, as the hand that guides the mouth to the breast</l>
<l rend="indent4">            of a flower-eyed girl who has given birth to a son,</l>
<l rend="indent">            if [their] friends are in front [of them(?) and] give it [to them],</l>
<l>        courteous people will even absorb poison, abundantly(?).<note place="foot">This seems to be an aphorism, this time in the middle of a poem, as usual syntactically completely unmarked as an independent sentence, and as usual unclear as to its precise impact. A striking parallel, as pointed out to me by J.L.C., is to be found in <term xml:lang="ta">Kuṟaḷ</term> 580 (<term xml:lang="ta">peyakkaṇṭu nañcuṇ ṭamaivar nayattakka nākarikam vēṇṭu pavar</term> "Those who desire to cultivate that degree of urbanity which all shall love, even after swallowing the poison served to them by their friends, will be friendly with them.")</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">            Even if [your] heart has no pleasure</l>
<l rend="indent3">            in sleeping by the shoulder of my friend with pretty thin hair,</l>
<l>        turn to(?) it for my sake [and] have pity.</l>
<l>        Apart from you<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains kaṇ here to mean "support", for which he gives Kal. 88.8 as a parallel (which, however, for once is understood in a different way by Nacc.: <term xml:lang="ta">niṉṉuṭaiya kaṇṇiṉil aruṇōkkiṉaip peṟilaṉṟi</term>).</note> she has nothing else.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
